      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm working on an embedded c++ project for an automotive control unit and we're seeing a slow memory leak. the system runs fine for a few hours but then eventually runs out of available ram and crashes. i don't see any obvious missing deletes in my main loop. how should i go about systematically finding where the leak is happening?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A memory leak in an automotive control unit can be a real challenge. You'll want to track down the source of the leak, and I'd recommend using a combination of tools to help you identify the issue. First, enable the heap debugging tool in your compiler, which will provide a detailed report of all memory allocations and deallocations in your program. This will give you a good starting point to investigate the leak.\n\nNext, consider using a memory profiling tool like Valgrind or AddressSanitizer, which can help you detect memory leaks and identify the source of the issue. These tools can provide a detailed report of all memory allocations and deallocations, as well as information on the objects that are not being freed.\n\nAnother approach is to use a memory leak detection library, such as MemoryLeakDetector, which can help you identify memory leaks in your code. These libraries often provide a way to track memory allocations and deallocations, and can alert you when a memory leak is detected.\n\nIt's also worth noting that some memory leaks can be caused by objects that are not being properly destroyed, such as objects that are created on the stack but not properly released. Consider using a memory debugging tool to help you identify these types of leaks.\n\nIn the meantime",
      "source": "target",
